GraphQL API Reference

Welcome to the OpenCRVS GraphQL API reference! This is an exhaustive list of all available endpoints and their respective schemas.

Learn how to authenticate to the API in the Getting started -guide: https://todo-todo.opencrvs.org

FHIR-endpoint documentation: https://todo-todo.opencrvs.org

API Endpoints
http://localhost:7070/graphql
Headers
# Your API token from the auth `/token` endpoint
Authorization: Bearer <YOUR_TOKEN_HERE>

Queries

fetchBirthRegistration

Response

Returns a BirthRegistration

Arguments
Name Description
id - ID!

Example

Query
query fetchBirthRegistration($id: ID!) {
  fetchBirthRegistration(id: $id) {
    id
    _fhirIDMap
    registration {
      ...RegistrationFragment
    }
    child {
      ...PersonFragment
    }
    mother {
      ...PersonFragment
    }
    father {
      ...PersonFragment
    }
    informant {
      ...RelatedPersonFragment
    }
    eventLocation {
      ...LocationFragment
    }
    birthType
    questionnaire {
      ...QuestionnaireQuestionFragment
    }
    weightAtBirth
    attendantAtBirth
    otherAttendantAtBirth
    childrenBornAliveToMother
    foetalDeathsToMother
    lastPreviousLiveBirth
    createdAt
    updatedAt
    history {
      ...HistoryFragment
    }
  }
}
Variables
{"id": 4}
Response
{
  "data": {
    "fetchBirthRegistration": {
      "id": "4",
      "_fhirIDMap": Map,
      "registration": Registration,
      "child": Person,
      "mother": Person,
      "father": Person,
      "informant": RelatedPerson,
      "eventLocation": Location,
      "birthType": "abc123",
      "questionnaire": [QuestionnaireQuestion],
      "weightAtBirth": 123.45,
      "attendantAtBirth": "abc123",
      "otherAttendantAtBirth": "xyz789",
      "childrenBornAliveToMother": 123,
      "foetalDeathsToMother": 123,
      "lastPreviousLiveBirth": "2007-12-03",
      "createdAt": "2007-12-03",
      "updatedAt": "2007-12-03",
      "history": [History]
    }
  }
}

fetchLocationWiseEventMetrics

Response

Returns [LocationWiseEstimationMetric!]

Arguments
Name Description
timeStart - String!
timeEnd - String!
locationId - String
event - String!

Example

Query
query fetchLocationWiseEventMetrics(
  $timeStart: String!,
  $timeEnd: String!,
  $locationId: String,
  $event: String!
) {
  fetchLocationWiseEventMetrics(
    timeStart: $timeStart,
    timeEnd: $timeEnd,
    locationId: $locationId,
    event: $event
  ) {
    total
    withinTarget
    within1Year
    within5Years
    estimated
    locationId
    locationName
  }
}
Variables
{
  "timeStart": "xyz789",
  "timeEnd": "xyz789",
  "locationId": "xyz789",
  "event": "xyz789"
}
Response
{
  "data": {
    "fetchLocationWiseEventMetrics": [
      {
        "total": 987,
        "withinTarget": 987,
        "within1Year": 987,
        "within5Years": 123,
        "estimated": 987,
        "locationId": "xyz789",
        "locationName": "xyz789"
      }

  }

  $event: String!,
  $filterBy: String!,
  $skip: Int!,
  $size: Int!
) {
  getRegistrationsListByFilter(
    timeStart: $timeStart,
    timeEnd: $timeEnd,
    locationId: $locationId,
    event: $event,
    filterBy: $filterBy,
    skip: $skip,
    size: $size
  ) {
    ... on TotalMetricsByRegistrar {
      ...TotalMetricsByRegistrarFragment
    }
    ... on TotalMetricsByLocation {
      ...TotalMetricsByLocationFragment
    }
    ... on TotalMetricsByTime {
      ...TotalMetricsByTimeFragment
    }
  }

Example

Query
query getSystemRoles(
  $title: String,
  $value: ComparisonInput,
  $role: String,
  $active: Boolean,
  $sortBy: String,
  $sortOrder: String
) {
  getSystemRoles(
    title: $title,
    value: $value,
    role: $role,
    active: $active,
    sortBy: $sortBy,
    sortOrder: $sortOrder
  ) {
    id
    value
    roles {
      ...RoleFragment
    }
    active
  }
}
Variables
{
  "title": "abc123",
  "value": ComparisonInput,
  "role": "xyz789",

ID

Description

The ID scalar type represents a unique identifier, often used to refetch an object or as key for a cache. The ID type appears in a JSON response as a String; however, it is not intended to be human-readable. When expected as an input type, any string (such as "4") or integer (such as 4) input value will be accepted as an ID.

Example
"4"
